!!! 5
%html
  %head
    %meta{:content => "text/html;charset=utf-8", "http-equiv" => "Content-Type"}/
    %title Simple Atoms Model
    %script{:src => "../../vendor/modernizr/modernizr.js", :type => "text/javascript"}
    %script{:src => "../../vendor/d3/d3.v2.js", :type => "text/javascript"}
    %script{:src => "../../vendor/jquery/jquery.min.js", :type => "text/javascript"}
    %script{:src => "../../vendor/science.js/science.js", :type => "text/javascript"}
    %script{:src => "../../vendor/science.js/science.stats.js", :type => "text/javascript"}
    %script{:src => "http://use.typekit.com/hdw8ayt.js", :type => "text/javascript"}
    %script{:type => "text/javascript"}
      try{Typekit.load();}catch(e){}
      if (!Modernizr.svg) { window.location = '../../browser-upgrade.html'; }
    %link{:href => "http://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Open+Sans:400italic,700italic,300italic,400,300,700&subset=latin,greek,latin-ext", :rel => "stylesheet", :type => "text/css"}/
    %link{:href => "../examples.css", :rel => "stylesheet", :type => "text/css"}/
    %link{:href => "../../lab/css/components.css", :rel => "stylesheet", :type => "text/css"}/
    %link{:href => "application.css", :rel => "stylesheet", :type => "text/css"}/
  %body
    #header
      %a#logo(href="http://www.concord.org/")
        %img(src="../../resources/layout/cc-logo.png")
      %h1
        %a(href="http://lab.dev.concord.org/examples/simple-atoms-model/simple-atoms-model.html") Simple Atoms Model
      %img#fullscreen(class="size-full wp-image-1880" src="../../resources/layout/fullscreen.gif")
    #content
      %ul
        %li.top
          #viz
            %ul
              %li.top
                #molecule-container
              %li
                #thermometer
                #therm_text
            %ul
              %li
                .component_group
                  .slider_container
                    Intermolecular Attraction
                    .slider_content
                      #attraction_slider
                    .left_half
                      weaker
                    .right_half
                      stronger
                    .below
                      Attractive Force
              %li
                .component_group
                  .slider_container
                    Force Interactions
                    .left_half
                    .content
                      %div{:style=> "width: 10em; height: 2em; display: inline-block; margin: 0.5em"}
                        Coulomb
                        %input(id="coulomb-forces-checkbox" type="checkbox")
                    .below
                      %input(id="lennard-jones-forces-checkbox" type="checkbox" checked)
              %li
                .component_group
                  .slider_container
                    Change Temperature
                    .content
                      %div{:style=> "width: 10em; height: 2em; display: inline-block; margin: 0.5em"}
                        %button#cool_button(type="button" class="left_edge" value="colder")colder
                        %button#heat_button(type="button" class="right_edge" value="hotter")hotter

        %li.top
          #description-right
            %p
              A computational simulation of a collection of simple &ldquo;atoms&rdquo; which are free to move in two dimensions. The force between pairs of atoms is modeled using a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lennard-Jones_potential" target="_blank">Lennard-Jones</a> potential. So that you can more easily explore how temperature and intermolecular attraction strength affect phase changes, intermolecular attractions are much stronger in this simulation than they are for the equivalent &ldquo;featureless&rdquo; and nonreactive atoms found in Nature, those of the noble gases.
            %p
              When the Coulomb force interaction checkbox is checked,
              atoms also experience electrostatic interactions. Opposite  charges of +1 or -1 are evenly distributed among the atoms, and particles with opposite charge attract, while atoms with the same charge repel each other, according to Coulomb's Law. Atoms with a positive charge appear blue, atoms with a negative
              charge appear red.


    %script{:src => "../../lab/lab.js", :type => "text/javascript"}
    %script{:src => "application.js", :type => "text/javascript"}